Raw data

Data structure

Publicly available testing data are daily aggregated, splitting by Outcome_tests:

# A tibble: 4 x 4
  Date       Number_of_tests Outcome_tests  Week
  <date>               <dbl> <chr>         <int>
1 2020-01-24               0 Positive          4
2 2020-01-24               3 Negative          4
3 2020-01-25               0 Positive          4
4 2020-01-25               4 Negative          4

Example: first case:

# A tibble: 2 x 4
  Date       Number_of_tests Outcome_tests  Week
  <date>               <dbl> <chr>         <int>
1 2020-02-24               1 Positive          9
2 2020-02-24              47 Negative          9

7 day rolling average

testing %<>% 
  group_by(Date) %>% 
  summarise(Number_of_tests = sum(Number_of_tests)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(Number_of_tests_07da = zoo::rollmean(Number_of_tests, k = 7, fill = NA)) %>% 
  mutate(Week = as.integer(format(Date, format = "%V"))) %>% 
  arrange(Date)

Time adjusted GAM models

Daily tests

min_date <- as.numeric(min(testing$Date))

testing %<>% 
  arrange(Date) %>% 
  mutate(Day = as.numeric(Date) - min_date + 1)

testing %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Number_of_tests)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 100)


model_time_day_01 <- gam(Number_of_tests ~  s(Day, bs = 'cs', k = 28), 
                         data = testing, 
                         family = scat(link = "identity"))

summary(model_time_day_01)

Weekly data

testing_weekly <- testing %>% 
  filter(Date <= as.Date("2020-12-20")) %>% 
  # filter(Week > 4) %>% 
  group_by(Week) %>% 
  summarize(Number_of_tests = sum(Number_of_tests))

testing_weekly %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Number_of_tests)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10000)


model_time_week_01 <- gam(Number_of_tests ~  s(Week, bs = 'cs', k = 14), 
                          data = testing_weekly, 
                          family = scat(link = "identity"))

summary(model_time_week_01)
